The Leverage Question
---------------------

Steven Cahall, an equity analyst at Wells Fargo,
recently published a comprehensive report ( https://puck.news/wp-content/up=
loads/2024/12/Wells-Fargo-MEDIA-The-2025-Oracle-12.19.24-1.pdf?utm_campaign=
=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F22%2F24%29&utm_content=3DDry+Powder+-+S=
UBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F18%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustom=
er.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) on how he thinks a variety of media a=
nd media-related assets will fare next year. I found Steve=E2=80=99s predic=
tions particularly interesting=E2=80=94especially the fact that his top the=
me for 2025 is, in his words, the =E2=80=9Clegacy cable roll-up.=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0

Steve=E2=80=99s report is
filled with intriguing tidbits and observations. For instance, while Comcas=
t only coughed up the revenue generated by SpinCo in fiscal 2024 (approxima=
tely $7 billion), Cahall estimates that SpinCo=E2=80=99s EBITDA will be abo=
ut $2.4 billion, or a hefty EBITDA margin of 34.3 percent. He tagged a 4x E=
BITDA multiple on the assets, giving SpinCo an estimated enterprise value o=
f $8.5 billion, inclusive of $2.1 billion of debt, or debt of less than 1x =
estimated 2024 EBITDA. That would certainly
qualify SpinCo as =E2=80=9Cwell-capitalized,=E2=80=9D although it is decide=
dly unexciting, and it should be able to carry more debt and still be attra=
ctive to investors, if Comcast would only consider a private equity partner=
 to underpin the capital structure.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Cahall=E2=80=99s analysis values the equity of SpinCo at around $1.50 per C=
omcast share, providing shareholders an incremental, but hardly consequenti=
al, 3.8
percent boost to Comcast=E2=80=99s share price. He predicts the combination=
 of SpinCo and existing Comcast would result in a share price of $40.47, a =
modest bump to Comcast=E2=80=99s $39 share price on December 17, the date o=
f his report. =E2=80=9CSpinCo is a positive for [Comcast], but not a game-c=
hanger,=E2=80=9D he wrote.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

That=E2=80=99s an understatement, to be honest. A lot of work and expense w=
ill go into generating that extra $1.50
per share, and it=E2=80=99s hard to imagine that Roberts and his executives=
 would go through all this trouble for such a meager pop. With a P.E. firm =
along for the ride and more debt piled atop SpinCo, the pop for Comcast cou=
ld be far larger. =E2=80=9CWe think the bigger implication from the transac=
tion is the precedent + opportunities it might set for WBD and PARA, and wh=
ether SpinCo could act as a consolidator of other networks to improve scale=
,=E2=80=9D Cahall continued.

=C2=A0

In his report, Cahall predicted that SpinCo=E2=80=99s most likely near-term=
 acquisition target will not be either WBD=E2=80=99s or Paramount Global=E2=
=80=99s linear assets. They each have too much debt, he argued, and he thin=
ks that Comcast=E2=80=99s SpinCo shareholders don=E2=80=99t =E2=80=9Cwant l=
everage.=E2=80=9D (I=E2=80=99m not convinced, as you know.) =E2=80=9CToo mu=
ch debt on a levered asset risks erasing the equity value,=E2=80=9D Cahall =
wrote. That=E2=80=99s obviously true.=C2=A0

