Instead, he thinks SpinCo will more likely try to go after
Starz, which is the forlorn stepchild in the crazy Lionsgate universe, or A=
MC Networks, which has a market value these days of around $400 million. Th=
ey are =E2=80=9Cnear-term merger candidates to build scale, as they have lo=
w leverage and relatively unique prestige dramas that could be seen as comp=
lementary to the mostly nonfiction content of the [Comcast] nets.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

As for Zaz=E2=80=99s linear TV assets, Cahall wrote that
while they could be spun off or sold, =E2=80=9Cit=E2=80=99s much more diffi=
cult than initial optimism might be implying.=E2=80=9D The fact that WBD=E2=
=80=99s stock traded up some 15 percent on the news of the reorganization w=
hile its bonds traded down, he argued, implies that the market is expecting=
 some sort of leveraged spinoff of these assets. But he thinks that private=
 equity won=E2=80=99t be able to partner with WBD=E2=80=99s linear assets, =
even if Zaz gives them the green light. He reasons that at 4x 2025 estimate=
d EBITDA of $6.7
billion, WBD=E2=80=99s linear assets (CNN, TNT and TBS, etcetera) would hav=
e a valuation of $27 billion=E2=80=94too rich for a private equity firm or =
even a group of private equity firms.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

I disagree with Steve, here. I believe Zaz could sell private equity a 30 p=
ercent stake in his SpinCo for $8.1 billion=E2=80=94a big check, yes, but n=
ot an insurmountable one, especially if a consortium of firms comes togethe=
r for the
deal. (After all, TPG is writing a check for $7.6 billion for the 70 percen=
t of DirecTV it doesn=E2=80=99t already own.) Cahall also thinks that a 4x =
EBITDA purchase multiple may be too high an entry point for the savvy priva=
te equity crowd. I=E2=80=99ll concede that point. =E2=80=9CSomething well b=
ought is half sold,=E2=80=9D Gus Levy, the wily senior partner of Goldman S=
achs, used to say.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Cahall also thinks WBD=E2=80=99s
bondholders would drive a hard bargain with Zaz in order to be offloaded on=
to the WBD spinco and would need =E2=80=9Ca lot of coaxing=E2=80=9D to go a=
long. He predicts 2x leverage on WBD=E2=80=99s spinco would be possible. If=
 so, that would be something like $13.5 billion of debt, which would deleve=
r the remaining WBD to around $25 billion.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Cahall predicted the remaining WBD, sans linear, would have EBITDA of $2.8 =
billion in 2025, a
still-unattractive 9x leverage. He urged caution, at least for equity inves=
tors. =E2=80=9CThere is reason to be optimistic that Studios/D.T.C. could b=
e valuable as both a stand-alone and takeout vehicle,=E2=80=9D he wrote. =
=E2=80=9CBut, even using [Comcast=E2=80=99s] 15x multiple on Sky, it implie=
s to us that much of the M&A potential for WBD is already priced in. We=E2=
=80=99re therefore loath to chase it here as we think a lot has to happen p=
rior to monetization of a separation.=E2=80=9D

The Disney Piece
----------------

Cahall was clear that he doesn=E2=80=99t think Disney will participate in
the linear spinco feeding frenzy. Its television assets, he noted, =E2=80=
=9Crepresent the core content that=E2=80=99s on streaming,=E2=80=9D adding =
that he expects Comcast and Disney to keep NBC and ABC, respectively, since=
 they are =E2=80=9Cstrategic assets for sports distribution.=E2=80=9D As fo=
r Paramount, he thinks the new owners will want to keep CBS, which has valu=
able NFL and college basketball rights, but that BET/VH1 may be jettisoned,=
 as has been long under consideration. As for MTV, Comedy Central, and Nick=
elodeon, he
thinks those assets are still under =E2=80=9Cstrategic review.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

In sum, Steve concluded that =E2=80=9Cthere is something there=E2=80=9D whe=
n it comes to the potential for a larger linear TV roll-up, with the most l=
ikely path being some combination of Comcast=E2=80=99s SpinCo and WBD=E2=80=
=99s presumed spinco, with AMC and Starz being picked up along the way in s=
tock deals. That kind of roll-up, Cahall estimates, would have an enterpris=
e value of $38
billion, including $17.2 billion of net debt, $13.4 billion of which would =
come from WBD. I=E2=80=99m not sure if it=E2=80=99ll happen this way or som=
e other way. But what=E2=80=99s clear is that we appear to have arrived, af=
ter much strategic fretting, at a time when something like this will defini=
tely happen, and I suspect it=E2=80=99ll all start coming together, one way=
 or another, in the first half of 2025.=C2=A0

