px;line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong>David Zaslav</strong>=E2=80=99s de=
cision to quarantine Warner
Bros. Discovery=E2=80=99s linear assets, thus creating two operating divisi=
ons at the company, is obviously a prelude to deal activity, probably in 20=
25 or 2026. But I actually think the deal opportunities on the cable side a=
re less interesting to contemplate. I still believe that a combination of N=
BCU and WBD, with or without their respective linear TV assets (but increas=
ingly looking like without), is not only viable, but may even be necessary =
for the two companies to compete long-term with the likes
of Disney, Amazon, Apple, and Google. But that will only happen if Zaz and =
Roberts can reach some sort of amicable d=C3=A9tente on structure, ownershi=
p, and control.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p=
><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">That=E2=80=99s a complex negotiat=
ion, given the egos involved, but I still think there=E2=80=99s hope, espec=
ially since the parties in question were able to reach a friendly enough ag=
reement on a new =E2=80=9Cmust-carry=E2=80=9D deal to keep WBD=E2=80=99s ca=
ble channels on
Comcast=E2=80=99s cable distribution network. I=E2=80=99ve also speculated =
on the likelihood that private equity, with its hundreds of billions in dry=
 powder, will want to get involved with these high cash-flowing but declini=
ng assets=E2=80=94the precise set of conditions that could facilitate the c=
onversations between the two companies. The gold standard for this kind of =
structure remains what TPG and AT&amp;T agreed to do with DirecTV in 2022. =
First, TPG bought 30 percent of DirecTV, allowing AT&amp;T to deconsolidate=
 the
assets from its financial statements (and to stop having to answer Wall Str=
eet=E2=80=99s questions about the decline). Then, in September, TPG agreed =
to buy the 70 percent of DirecTV that it didn=E2=80=99t already own. (Discl=
osure: TPG, as you know, is an investor in Puck.)=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"marg=
in:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Yes, the Comcast =
executives continue to claim that there will be no private equity in SpinCo=
, but let=E2=80=99s wait and see. I note with interest that Zaz has not sai=
d
anything material about how much leverage he=E2=80=99ll end up putting on W=
BD=E2=80=99s linear TV assets in the event of a spinoff, or whether he woul=
d allow private equity to play. I take that as Zaz=E2=80=99s own <em>Everyt=
hing is on the table</em> moment. He certainly is well familiar with TPG=E2=
=80=99s DirecTV deal, and I=E2=80=99ve got to believe if he can extract mor=
e value from his cable assets by partnering with private equity, he=E2=80=
=99ll do it. Could Zaz be on the verge of a real wishbone split here=E2=80=
=94unloading the cable nets while
eventually combining his digital assets with NBCU=E2=80=99s, thus completin=
g the final act of his public L.B.O. experiment, and extracting real value =
for his patient shareholders? (This is not investment advice.) We=E2=80=99l=
l have to wait to see.</p></div>
