JhIiwibGlua19pZCI6MjAyNTMwMn0/c1355dbc50dbdbacc4aca3cea86cd9c4ae3ce73af4c19=
954a597e1a7575c07ca" style=3D"text-decoration:underline;color:#d40000;">rep=
ort</a> on how he thinks a variety of media and media-related assets will f=
are next year. I found Steve=E2=80=99s predictions particularly interesting=
=E2=80=94especially the fact that his top theme for 2025 is, in his words, =
the =E2=80=9Clegacy cable roll-up.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;m=
argin-bottom:0px;"><br/>Steve=E2=80=99s report is
filled with intriguing tidbits and observations. For instance, while Comcas=
t only coughed up the <em>revenue</em> generated by SpinCo in fiscal 2024 (=
approximately $7 billion), Cahall estimates that SpinCo=E2=80=99s EBITDA wi=
ll be about $2.4 billion, or a hefty EBITDA margin of 34.3 percent. He tagg=
ed a 4x EBITDA multiple on the assets, giving SpinCo an estimated enterpris=
e value of $8.5 billion, inclusive of $2.1 billion of debt, or debt of less=
 than 1x estimated 2024 EBITDA. That would certainly
qualify SpinCo as =E2=80=9Cwell-capitalized,=E2=80=9D although it is decide=
dly unexciting, and it should be able to carry more debt and still be attra=
ctive to investors, if Comcast would only consider a private equity partner=
 to underpin the capital structure.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bo=
ttom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Cahall=E2=80=
=99s analysis values the equity of SpinCo at around $1.50 per Comcast share=
, providing shareholders an incremental, but hardly <em>consequential</em>,=
 3.8
percent boost to Comcast=E2=80=99s share price. He predicts the combination=
 of SpinCo and existing Comcast would result in a share price of $40.47, a =
modest bump to Comcast=E2=80=99s $39 share price on December 17, the date o=
f his report. =E2=80=9CSpinCo is a positive for [Comcast], but not a game-c=
hanger,=E2=80=9D he wrote.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;=
">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">That=E2=80=99s an unde=
rstatement, to be honest. A lot of work and expense will go into generating=
 that extra $1.50
per share, and it=E2=80=99s hard to imagine that Roberts and his executives=
 would go through all this trouble for such a meager pop. With a P.E. firm =
along for the ride and more debt piled atop SpinCo, the pop for Comcast cou=
ld be far larger. =E2=80=9CWe think the bigger implication from the transac=
tion is the precedent + opportunities it might set for WBD and PARA, and wh=
ether SpinCo could act as a consolidator of other networks to improve scale=
,=E2=80=9D Cahall continued.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=
=C2=A0
</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">In his report, Cahall predicted that SpinCo=E2=
=80=99s most likely near-term acquisition target will <em>not</em> be eithe=
r WBD=E2=80=99s or Paramount Global=E2=80=99s linear assets. They each have=
 too much debt, he argued, and he thinks that Comcast=E2=80=99s SpinCo shar=
eholders don=E2=80=99t =E2=80=9Cwant leverage.=E2=80=9D (I=E2=80=99m not co=
nvinced, as you know.) =E2=80=9CToo much debt on a levered asset risks eras=
ing the equity value,=E2=80=9D Cahall wrote. That=E2=80=99s obviously true.=
=C2=A0</p></div>
