bottom:32px;"><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;In=
ter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;=
line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Cahall was clear that he doesn=E2=80=99t think =
Disney will participate in
the linear spinco feeding frenzy. Its television assets, he noted, =E2=80=
=9Crepresent the core content that=E2=80=99s on streaming,=E2=80=9D adding =
that he expects Comcast and Disney to keep NBC and ABC, respectively, since=
 they are =E2=80=9Cstrategic assets for sports distribution.=E2=80=9D As fo=
r Paramount, he thinks the new owners will want to keep CBS, which has valu=
able NFL and college basketball rights, but that BET/VH1 may be jettisoned,=
 as has been long under consideration. As for MTV, Comedy Central, and Nick=
elodeon, he
thinks those assets are still under =E2=80=9Cstrategic review.=E2=80=9D</p>=
<p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">I=
n sum, Steve concluded that =E2=80=9Cthere is something there=E2=80=9D when=
 it comes to the potential for a larger linear TV roll-up, with the most li=
kely path being some combination of Comcast=E2=80=99s SpinCo and WBD=E2=80=
=99s <em>presumed</em> spinco, with AMC and Starz being picked up along the=
 way in stock deals. That kind of roll-up, Cahall estimates, would have an =
enterprise value of $38
billion, including $17.2 billion of net debt, $13.4 billion of which would =
come from WBD. I=E2=80=99m not sure if it=E2=80=99ll happen this way or som=
e other way. But what=E2=80=99s clear is that we appear to have arrived, af=
ter much strategic fretting, at a time when <em>something</em> like this wi=
ll definitely happen, and I suspect it=E2=80=99ll all start coming together=
, one way or another, in the first half of 2025.=C2=A0</p></div>
